\begin_layout Section
Generic Models
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this section, we present arguably, the simplest HV theories, one of which
 is for spin like systems (discrete Hilbert space) while the other is for
 phase space (continuous Hilbert Space) for spin-less particles.
 These models are essentially non-contextual completions of QM, which facilitate
 easy computation of value assignment to operators.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Discretely C-ingle Theory 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sub:Discretely-C-ingle-Theory"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The state of the system is 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\chi\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, defined on a discrete Hilbert space (spin like) and we wish to assign
 a value to an arbitrary operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=\sum_{a}a\left|a\right\rangle \left\langle a\right|$
\end_inset

, which has eigenvalues 
\begin_inset Formula $\{a_{\text{min}}=a_{1}\le a_{2}\dots\le a_{n}=a_{\text{max}}\}$
\end_inset

.
 This theory has the following postulates: 
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

1.
 Initial HV: Pick a 
\begin_inset Formula $c\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

, from a uniform random distribution.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

2.
 Assignment/Prediction: The value assigned to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 is given by finding the smallest 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
c\le\sum_{a'=a_{\text{min}}}^{a}\left|\left\langle a'|\chi\right\rangle \right|^{2}.
\]

\end_inset

 A measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

, would yield 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset

3.
 Update: After measuring an operator, the state must be updated (collapsed)
 in accordance with the rules of QM.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To see how this works, we restrict ourselves to a single spin case.
 Say 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|\chi\right\rangle =\cos\theta\left|0\right\rangle +\sin\theta\left|1\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}=\hat{\sigma}_{z}=\left|0\right\rangle \left\langle 0\right|-\left|1\right\rangle \left\langle 1\right|$
\end_inset

.
 Now, according to the postulates of this theory, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 will be assigned 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $c\le\cos^{2}\theta$
\end_inset

, else 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{A}$
\end_inset

 will be assigned 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 It follows then, from 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 being uniformly random in 
\begin_inset Formula $[0,1]$
\end_inset

, that the statistics agree with predictions of QM.
 The reader can convince him(her)self that the said scheme works in general,
 specifically for the PM situation.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We can clearly see that the assignment is non-contextual, since given an
 operator and a state (+ the hidden variable), the value is uniquely assigned.
 The assignment is non-multiplicative, because this scheme when applied
 to the PM situation, becomes effectively the same as the toy model (barring
 the statistics).
 We have already seen explicitly that the toy-model non-multiplicative.
 The theory is ofcourse invasive, for the state is updated after each measuremen
t.
\end_layout

