\begin_layout Proposition*
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}=\nabla S/m$
\end_inset

 in a continuously c-ingle theory, for a single particle, with one degree
 of freedom.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 quantify some property of a particle.
 To point to a particle, we can either use the variables 
\begin_inset Formula $c,t$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $x,t$
\end_inset

, since we know how 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

 are related.
 Thus, one can write 
\begin_inset Formula $f(c,t)$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,t)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Foot
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
If you think that the two functions should be different, then the notation
 is confusing you.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,t)=f(t,x)$
\end_inset

 should help resolve.
 The position of the arguments is not important, this is not like a computer
 function.
 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,t)$
\end_inset

 is the statement that 
\begin_inset Formula $f$
\end_inset

 is a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x,t$
\end_inset

.
 That's it.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 Now we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}\right]_{c}=\left[\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}\right]_{t}.\left[\frac{\partial q}{\partial t}\right]_{c}+\left[\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}\right]_{q},
\]

\end_inset

where we used 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x,t)$
\end_inset

 on the RHS.
 Note also that 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}$
\end_inset

 refers to the velocity of a given particle, thus it must equal 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\partial q/\partial t\right]{}_{c}$
\end_inset

.
 Now for 
\begin_inset Formula $f=\int_{-\infty}^{q}\left|\psi(q')\right|^{2}dq'=c$
\end_inset

, the LHS disappears.
 Consequently, we have 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\frac{\partial q}{\partial t}\right]_{c}=-\left[\frac{\partial f}{\partial t}\right]_{q}/\left[\frac{\partial f}{\partial q}\right]_{t},
\]

\end_inset

which is in a form which can be evaluated directly from the relation given.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\partial f/\partial q\right]_{t}=\left|\psi(q,t)\right|^{2}=R^{2}$
\end_inset

, if 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi=Re^{iS/\hbar}$
\end_inset

.
 It is easy to show that the probability current is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $\nabla S/m$
\end_inset

.
 Using 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[\partial\left|\psi(q,t)\right|/\partial t\right]_{q}=-\nabla.(R^{2}\nabla S/m)$
\end_inset

, which is effectively the probability conservation statement, derived from
 Schrodinger's equation, written in polar form, it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $-\left[\partial f/\partial t\right]_{q}=R^{2}\nabla S$
\end_inset

.
 Thus we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\dot{q}=\nabla S$
\end_inset

 as claimed.
\end_layout

