\begin_layout Section
The Verdict: Contextuality vs.
 Non-Multiplicativity
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have already constructed an explicit non-contextual model, which is consisten
t with QM.
 This model we knew had to be non-multiplicative.
 We will see how non-multiplicativity gives rise to what one might confuse
 to mean contextuality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The approach is to take some compatible observables, and to construct a
 `super-operator', a measurement of which can yield the values of all of
 these compatible observables in a single shot.
 We would see then, that the in-principle measurement outcome of observing
 these compatible operators, would not be consistent.
 Now this one might treat as contextuality, but according to the definition
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Peres-Mermin-Revisited"

\end_inset

, we note that this is non-multiplicativity, as per 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Multiplicativity"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let us construct an explicit situation and make more precise statements.
 Borrowing the notation from 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Multiplicativity"

\end_inset

, imagine 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{B}_{1}=\hat{\sigma}_{z}\otimes\hat{\mathbb{I}}=\left|00\right\rangle \left\langle 00\right|+\left|01\right\rangle \left\langle 01\right|-\left[\left|10\right\rangle \left\langle 10\right|+\left|11\right\rangle \left\langle 11\right|\right],
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{B}_{2}=\hat{\mathbb{I}}\otimes\hat{\sigma}_{z}=\left|10\right\rangle \left\langle 10\right|+\left|11\right\rangle \left\langle 11\right|-\left[\left|00\right\rangle \left\langle 00\right|+\left|01\right\rangle \left\langle 01\right|\right],
\]

\end_inset

while we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{C}=f(\{\hat{B}_{i}\})=0.\left|00\right\rangle \left\langle 00\right|+1.\left|01\right\rangle \left\langle 01\right|+2.\left|10\right\rangle \left\langle 10\right|+3.\left|11\right\rangle \left\langle 11\right|.
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

 maybe viewed as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{1}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{2}$
\end_inset

 and other operators 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{i}$
\end_inset

 which are constructed to obtain a maximally commuting set.
 A measurement of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

, will collapse the state into one of the states which are simultaneous
 eignkets of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Consequently, from the observed value of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

, one can deduce the values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}_{2}$
\end_inset

.
 Now consider 
\begin_inset Formula $\sqrt{2}\left|\chi\right\rangle =\left|10\right\rangle +\left|01\right\rangle $
\end_inset

, for which 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}(\hat{B}_{1})=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}(\hat{B}_{2})=1$
\end_inset

, using the discretely c-ingle theory (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sub:Discretely-C-ingle-Theory"

\end_inset

), with 
\begin_inset Formula $c<0.5$
\end_inset

.
 However, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}(\hat{C})=1$
\end_inset

, from which one can deduce that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 was 
\begin_inset Formula $+1$
\end_inset

, while 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{2}$
\end_inset

 was 
\begin_inset Formula $-1$
\end_inset

.
 This property itself, one may be tempted call contextuality, viz.
 the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 depends on whether it is measured alone or with the remaining 
\begin_inset Formula $\{B_{i}\}$
\end_inset

.
 However, it must be noted that 
\begin_inset Formula $B_{1}$
\end_inset

 has a well defined value, and so does 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus by our accepted definition, there's no contextuality.
 It is just that 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1}(\hat{C})\neq f(m_{1}(\hat{B}_{1}),m_{1}(\hat{B}_{2}),\dots)$
\end_inset

, viz.
 the theory is non-multiplicative.
 Note that after measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

 however, 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}(\hat{B}_{1})=+1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{2}(\hat{B}_{2})=-1$
\end_inset

 (for any value of 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

) consistent with those deduced by measuring 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Denouement
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have already learnt that the proof of `contextuality', infact requires
 three assumptions, (1) multiplicativity, (2) non-contextuality and (3)
 non-invasiveness.
 Here we were able to construct an explicit non-contextual theory (for spins)
 which is non-multiplactive, but invasive and completely consistent with
 QM.
 Succinctly stated, it satisfies (2) but neither (3) nor (1), serving as
 a counter-example to the claim that non-contextual hidden variable theories
 can't be consistent with QM.
 We also showed how the theory might be misconstrued to be contextual and
 provided a clarification.
 This is of interest because the contextuality arising in BM from the measuremen
t schemes, has been a source of confusion about the said notion, arising
 in the PM situation.
\end_layout

